before_you_start.browser_title = Before you start
before_you_start.title = Calculate the Residential Nil Rate Band (RNRB) for an estate
before_you_start.guidance1 = This service will work out any RNRB allowance which will increase the Inheritance Tax threshold for a person who has died.
before_you_start.guidance2 = You can claim an RNRB allowance for either:
before_you_start.guidance2.bullet1 = a home in the estate of someone who has died
before_you_start.guidance2.bullet2 = a home that was sold or downsized by the person who has died
before_you_start.guidance3 = You may be able to claim additional allowance if:
before_you_start.guidance3.bullet1 = the person who has died had been married during their lifetime and their spouse or civil partner died before them
before_you_start.sub_heading = Before you start
before_you_start.guidance4 = You’ll need to have certain details to work out the RNRB allowance for the estate.
before_you_start.guidance5 = You’ll need to have details of:
before_you_start.guidance5.bullet1 = any homes owned by the person who died
before_you_start.guidance5.bullet2 = the will and what was left to anyone from the estate
before_you_start.guidance5.bullet3 = what the person who has died owned and any debts that are being paid out of their estate, along with the values of these
before_you_start.guidance5.bullet4 = any home that the person who has died used to own but sold and downsized to a cheaper home before their death
before_you_start.guidance5.bullet5 = he estate of any spouse or civil partner if their death was before the person who has died and you are transferring any of their unused RNRB allowance - you will also need a completed IHT-436 form to claim this
before_you_start.guidance6 = When you have finished this service and have any allowance to claim, you will need to fill in an IHT-435 form.

